In Week 9, the pattern that had been forming since the start of the term came into sharp relief. The administration no longer treated law, agencies, or borders as fixed structures it had to work within, but as tools it could bend, bypass, or break to reach its aims. The week\'92s events showed a government that had learned how to move fast and in many directions at once, using speed and volume as a shield. Courts, unions, and state officials pushed back, and some won temporary relief. Yet the deeper story was not about single rulings or orders. It was about how much of the state could be repurposed in seven days when a president saw constraint as an insult rather than a duty. That shift in attitude drove everything else.\
\
At the close of the prior period, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:49 p.m. It ends Week 9 at the same public time, 7:49 p.m., but the hands have crept forward inside the mechanism. The net movement is 0.3 minutes toward midnight. That small shift reflects a balance between two forces. On one side, the White House used executive orders, emergency rhetoric, and allied agencies to dismantle education, hollow out social insurance, and turn immigration law into a weapon. On the other, federal judges, state attorneys general, and civil society groups secured restraining orders, blocked data grabs, and forced partial reversals. The clock did not lurch because resistance still had teeth. It moved at all because the presidency showed it was willing to ignore those teeth when they bit.\
\
The most stark clash came over deportations. The president invoked the 1798 Alien Enemies Act, a wartime law, to justify mass expulsions of Venezuelan and Salvadoran migrants in peacetime. Judge James Boasberg issued a temporary restraining order, then a verbal command to turn planes around. The administration let the flights continue to El Salvador anyway, then argued that once the planes left U.S. airspace, the court had no say. In the days that followed, reports showed that many deportees had no criminal record and that tattoos and rumors stood in for evidence of gang ties. Families set up WhatsApp helplines to track loved ones sent to a \'93terrorism confinement centre.\'94 In this episode, the law was not a limit. It was a script the executive rewrote on the fly.\
\
The defiance did not stop at noncompliance. The president called Judge Boasberg a \'93radical left lunatic\'94 and demanded his impeachment. A Texas congressman obliged, filing articles of impeachment against the sitting chief judge of the D.C. district court for the act of issuing a restraining order. The Department of Justice asked an appeals court to remove Boasberg from the case, claiming his orders lacked force once planes were in the air. White House press secretary Karoline Leavitt smeared the judge and his wife from the podium, casting them as partisan actors. In response, Chief Justice John Roberts took the rare step of rebuking the president in public, reminding the country that impeachment is not a remedy for disagreement with a ruling. The judiciary was still willing to speak. The question was whether the other branches were still willing to listen.\
\
Other judges tried to draw lines. Boasberg extended his block on deportations under the Alien Enemies Act for fourteen days and ordered the government to explain why his orders had been ignored. Another judge, Theodore Chuang, ruled that the dismantling of USAID by Elon Musk\'92s \'93Department of Government Efficiency\'94 likely violated the Constitution and ordered parts of the agency restored. A different court halted DOGE\'92s attempt to gain access to Social Security data, calling it a \'93fishing expedition\'94 and ordering any personal information already taken to be destroyed. Yet each of these rulings came with a shadow. In several cases, the administration either delayed compliance or continued its course until forced into a hearing. The pattern was clear. Courts could still write orders, but the executive now treated obedience as optional.\
\
While this legal struggle played out, the administration moved to reshape the civil service itself. The most sweeping step was the executive order to dismantle the Department of Education. Over several days, the president signed and then repeated orders directing Education Secretary Linda McMahon to begin closing the department, despite its creation by Congress. The orders framed the move as \'93empowering parents, states, and communities,\'94 but the substance was stark. Programs for students with disabilities and English learners were slated for elimination. Pell Grants and federal aid for low-income students were placed at risk. Management of the federal student loan portfolio was shifted to the Small Business Administration, an agency with no history in that field, while services for disabled students were pushed toward Health and Human Services. The civil service was being bent toward partisan and private ends.\
\
The practical effect was to hollow out the federal role in education while keeping just enough structure to claim that nothing vital had been lost. Online applications for income-driven student loan plans vanished from the Education Department\'92s website. The American Federation of Teachers sued, arguing that the halt in processing income-driven repayment plans violated federal law and left millions of borrowers in limbo. Teachers\'92 unions and Democratic officials warned that the executive orders were illegal because only Congress can close a department it created. Yet the orders had already set the machinery in motion, and the administration treated litigation as a cost of doing business rather than a reason to pause. The clock ticked while the cases wound through court.\
