The same logic reached beyond education into the country\'92s cultural and civic memory. DOGE teams arrived at the Institute of Museum and Library Services, sent employees home, swore in a new acting director, and canceled contracts and grants. This came on the heels of an order to eliminate the agency. Libraries and museums, which had long served as quiet anchors of civic education, suddenly found their federal support in question. At the Pentagon, offices dedicated to civilian harm mitigation and diversity were closed. Military websites quietly removed pages about Navajo Code Talkers, Black veterans, and women pilots, labeling broken links \'93DEI\'94 until public outcry forced a partial restoration. The pattern was not random austerity. It was a targeted thinning of institutions that teach a broad, plural story of the country.\
