Social insurance systems were pulled into the same vortex. Internal memos from the Social Security Administration revealed plans to require \'93internet identity proofing\'94 for phone-based benefit claims, forcing those without internet access\'97often elderly and disabled people\'97to appear in person. At the same time, SSA quietly froze the Enumeration Beyond Entry program, which had automatically issued Social Security numbers to newly authorized workers and new citizens. The freeze, never publicly announced, threatened to send tens of thousands of people a week into already strained field offices. Judges blocked DOGE from rummaging through SSA data, but the agency\'92s own policy shifts remained in place. The burden of \'93integrity\'94 fell on the most vulnerable claimants, while the political architects of the changes faced little scrutiny. The imbalance was stark.\
