Immigration policy became the sharpest edge of a new hierarchy of belonging. In one stroke, the Department of Homeland Security revoked temporary legal status for more than 530,000 immigrants from Cuba, Haiti, Nicaragua, and Venezuela, ending a parole program that had allowed them to live and work in the United States. The decision, signed by Homeland Security chief Kristi Noem, set an April deadline after which those without another status would be deportable. At the same time, ICE intensified raids on Chinese immigrants, including in sanctuary cities, and chartered flights to China. A Canadian with a valid work visa was detained for two weeks under harsh conditions. A German green-card holder was stripped naked and interrogated at Boston\'92s airport, pressured to surrender his status. A French scientist was denied entry after border agents read messages critical of the administration on his phone.\
