Universities sat at the intersection of these pressures. Columbia University saw $400 million in federal funding clawed back, then received a letter from the administration demanding a mask ban, the winding down of certain departments, and greater police powers on campus as conditions for restoring the money. The University of Pennsylvania had $175 million in funding frozen over its policies on transgender athletes. A federal taskforce was announced to investigate alleged antisemitism at ten major universities, while sixty more schools received warning letters. At the same time, individual scholars were targeted. Mahmoud Khalil, a Palestinian activist and permanent resident, was arrested under an obscure provision allowing deportation of foreign nationals deemed harmful to foreign policy. His detention, and the revocation of another student\'92s visa, sent a chill through international student communities. A Georgetown scholar, Badar Khan Suri, was detained by ICE over alleged ties to Hamas; a judge later barred his deportation, calling the case a test of free speech and due process.\
