The administration\'92s message to campuses was blunt. Dissent, especially around Palestine and U.S. foreign policy, could cost you your funding, your visa, or your freedom. When a Cornell PhD student, Momodou Taal, sued to block executive orders aimed at deporting foreign students involved in pro-Palestinian protests, ICE promptly asked him to surrender to immigration authorities. His lawyers rushed to court to prevent his detention. The timing made the point. Legal recourse itself could trigger enforcement. Universities, long seen as semi-autonomous spaces of debate, now had to weigh every protest and statement against the risk of federal retaliation.\
