These moves did not censor all criticism. They did something subtler. They narrowed the channels through which independent, fact-based information could reach large audiences, while leaving partisan and state-aligned narratives untouched or amplified. Radio Free Europe sued to restore its funding, arguing that the cuts violated law and the Constitution. The National Archives quietly confirmed that the use of a standardized signature graphic in the Federal Register did not invalidate President Biden\'92s pardons, countering the president\'92s claim that those pardons were \'93void\'94 because they were signed by autopen. Yet the damage to public understanding was done. The president\'92s assertion that he could nullify a predecessor\'92s pardons by decree signaled to allies and enemies alike that legal finality was now a matter of political will.\
