The fusion of private wealth and state power deepened. Elon Musk\'92s Starlink internet system was installed across the White House campus as a \'93donation,\'94 raising procurement and security concerns. DOGE, the Musk-linked \'93department of government efficiency,\'94 gained access to unclassified federal records and software systems by executive order, until courts stepped in to limit its reach at Social Security. The Federal Aviation Administration canceled a $2.4 billion contract with Verizon and shifted airspace management to Starlink, prompting senators to demand an investigation into possible corruption. At the Pentagon, Musk received a private briefing on U.S. war plans for a potential conflict with China, even as his companies maintained deep business ties with that country. After press reports, the White House denied that classified material had been shared and the president conceded that war plans should not be given to a businessman with such interests. But the briefing had already been scheduled, and Musk\'92s role as both contractor and informal adviser was plain.\
