Security policy itself moved toward a more militarized and privatized model. The administration ordered airstrikes in Yemen without congressional authorization, killing dozens, including children, and vowed \'93overwhelming lethal force\'94 until Houthi attacks on shipping ceased. At home, plans emerged for a militarized buffer zone along the New Mexico border, staffed by active-duty troops empowered to detain migrants until they could be handed to immigration officers. The design appeared crafted to skirt the Posse Comitatus Act\'92s limits on military involvement in domestic law enforcement. Erik Prince lobbied for a $25 billion scheme to privatize mass deportations, and the president suggested that those who vandalized Tesla property should face twenty-year sentences in El Salvador\'92s prisons. The line between national defense and domestic control grew thinner, and private actors stood ready to profit from both.\
