Against this backdrop, state and civil society actors tried to hold ground. Democratic attorneys general organized community impact hearings across the country, gathering testimony from people harmed by federal firings, deportations, and funding cuts. They filed roughly ten lawsuits against the administration, winning temporary restraining orders in nearly all of them. These orders halted or reversed actions such as grant \'93pauses,\'94 USAID\'92s dismantling, and DOGE\'92s data grabs. Teachers\'92 unions sued over student loan repayment plans. Environmental groups faced a $660 million defamation verdict in North Dakota for their role in Dakota Access pipeline protests, a ruling that threatened to chill future activism. Yet even as courts sided with challengers in many cases, the administration\'92s willingness to ignore or delay compliance forced these actors into a constant defensive crouch. The strain was visible.\
