Abroad, the administration continued to pull away from traditional alliances and accountability structures. It froze intelligence and weapons packages for Ukraine, withdrew from an international body investigating responsibility for the invasion of that country, and considered relinquishing the U.S. role as NATO\'92s Supreme Allied Commander Europe. Contracts that had helped track Russian abductions of Ukrainian children were canceled. A ceasefire call with Vladimir Putin was framed as a step toward peace, but Russian demands centered on ending U.S. military aid to Ukraine. At the same time, the United States refused, for the first time, a Mexican request for water under a 1944 treaty, citing Mexico\'92s shortfalls and the needs of American farmers. Even a cross-border library shared with Canada became a site of new restrictions, as Canadians were told they must now pass through formal customs to enter a building that had long symbolized open cooperation.\
